SIMPLE: merger
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Merger
<hw>Mer"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, merges.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An absorption of one estate, or one
contract, in another, or of a minor offense in a greater.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The combining of two groups into a unified single
group under a single leadership, with voluntary participation by the
leaders or management of both groups.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Business,
Finance)</fld> <def>The combining of two commercial enterprises into a
unified single enterprise under a single management, with voluntary
participation by both parties; <as>as, the <ex>merger</ex> of
<corpn>Daimler-Benz</corpn> and <corpn>Chrysler</corpn> into
<corpn>Daimler-Chrysler</corpn> created a powerful competitor in the
automobile manufacturing industry</as>. Compare
<contr>acquisition</contr> and <contr>takeover</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merging</ent>⟦br⟧
